Reasoning: The claim is strongly supported by multiple sources. Granuloma formation is explicitly described as a T-cell-dependent inflammatory response (Paper ID: 10222057). The presence of "granulomatous inflammation" and its potential pathological consequences are also highlighted (Paper ID: 8426644). Furthermore, immune cells within and around granulomas, such as macrophages, are identified as sources of inflammatory cytokines, toxic radicals, and lipid mediators, which contribute to tissue damage (Paper ID: W2016293419). The role of TNF in stimulating granuloma formation during the immune response (Paper ID: 40427602) and the involvement of the IL6 pathway in intensifying inflammation in granulomas (Paper ID: 0f8cfb4eaf2ddc3b2f0b2c2adae8fa1c79ce9443) further corroborate the claim. The structured recruitment of immune cells to granulomas also localizes and limits the inflammatory response, indicating their active role in this process (Paper ID: 40427602).

